<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / UK Company News: RH Macy records Dollars 671m loss
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
R. H. MACY, the large US department store chain which filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection earlier this year, yesterday announced an after-tax
loss of Dollars 671.6m in the three months to February 1 - covering the key
Christmas sales period.
The figures, however, are confused by various write-off and restructuring
charges.
The company made a Dollars 499.8m loss before interest and reorganisation
expenses, but after a Dollars 284.9m unusual item. This compared with a
Dollars 182.5m surplus in the same period a year earlier - when there were
no unusual items.
The 'above-the-line' unusual items derive principally from a Dollars 241m
write-off of goodwill, in turn related to the purchase of the I. Magnin and
Bullocks divisions from Federated Department Stores in 1988. There is also a
Dollars 40m charge to cover the costs of realigning the group in the 'east'
and 'west' divisions.
The interest charge for the period dropped sharply, to Dollars 68.9m from
Dollars 178.3m but Macy then incurred a further Dollars 102.9m charge for
reorganisation expenses. Within this figure, the retail group is charging
Dollars 76m for store closings, Dollars 16m for deferred debt expenses, and
Dollars 8m for the write-off of preferred stock issuance costs.
Sales for the period totalled Dollars 2.05bn, a decrease of 6.4 per cent
from the same quarter in 1990-1. On a same-store basis, Macy said that the
fall was slightly reduced, to a 3.4 per cent decline.
For the first six months of the financial year, Macy's sales now total
Dollars 3.66bn - a 0.5 per cent fall on a comparable store basis.
Macy added that cash and cash equivalents on hand at March 13 totalled
Dollars 250m. It added that it has not yet used the Dollars 600m
debtor-in-possession financing facility which has been approved by the
bankruptcy court.
It said that it does not expect to do so in the spring season, although part
of the facility has been committed for overseas letters of credit.
</TEXT>
