<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / High turnout in S African poll
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATTI WALDMEIR and MICHAEL HOLMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   CAPE TOWN, JOHANNESBURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OUTSIDE the Jan van Riebeeck school polling station in Cape Town yesterday
there was a consensus: everyone in the 100-metre queue planned to vote 'yes'
in South Africa's make-or-break referendum - or if not, they were keeping
quiet about it.
There was a big turnout, with long queues forming at many polling booths
around the country as whites cast their votes in the most important poll in
South Africa's history.
'In my 40 years in politics I have never, never seen a voting turnout as
high as the one for this referendum,' said one anti-apartheid politician.
About 70 per cent of the 3.3m white electorate cast their votes, with
polling as high as 80 per cent in some areas.
Reformers and the right-wing opponents were both predicting that they would
be the victors when the outcome is announced this morning.
For a day at least, the intense rivalry of the campaign was set aside. Some
polling stations, festooned with colourful posters, had an almost festive
air. Party officials on duty, Conservatives and reformists alike, carefully
tended their portable braaivleis (barbecues), enjoying a ritual that
transcends party politics.
The day passed without serious incident. The violence that has racked
townships in the three weeks since President FW de Klerk called the
referendum abated yesterday.
By 9am hundreds of voters from the comfortable Cape Town suburb of Gardens
had passed through the school gates, clearly sharing a sense of the
momentousness of the occasion. Voter after voter proclaimed that there was
only one choice in the poll: 'Yes, of course.' Yes for peace, yes for
prosperity, yes for international sport and investment.
Given the relatively liberal politics of Cape Town - worlds away from the
harsh racist attitudes prevalent elsewhere - a majority 'yes' vote from
Gardens would be scarcely surprising. Most voters said they did not expect
their lives to change much if they voted 'yes' for power-sharing with
blacks.
Outside the City Hall polling station in Durbanville, just outside Cape
Town, one voter put it this way: 'A 'yes' vote won't make any difference at
all to my life. But a 'no' vote would be disaster.' Asked whether 'yes'
meant he would accept a black man as president, he hesitated, looking around
for a way to escape the question, before conceding: 'Well, maybe in a few
years.'
Voters in neighbouring Kraaifontein, a blue-collar suburb which is expected
to vote resoundingly 'no', have a more immediate worry: squatters. Mr Frank
Kratz, a former white settler in South West Africa, now Namibia, insisted
that the town was surrounded by 50,000 squatters. 'Kraaifontein knows that
the new South Africa means squatters. And they are voting no,' he said.
On the edge of the town, the squatters who have so upset Mr Kratz and his
neighbours sit outside hovels made of tin and packing cases, plastic and
cardboard. The camp has no water, no toilets, no amenities.
A local resident said he wanted whites to vote 'yes'. 'If they vote yes,
then maybe we will get jobs, and they will do something about this place.'
Even so, he seemed far from persuaded.
Budget options, Page 4
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 20
</PAGE>
