<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Observer: Enterprising initiative
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
GrandMet chairman Sir Allen Sheppard tells me he is well pleased at the
response to his round robin letter about the need to support the party
which, since 1979, has been promoting the renewed spirit of enterprise in
Britain.
Although far from all of his counterparts were willing to 'put their heads
above the parapet', he was 'quite amazed' that two out of every three he
approached were ready to sign his letter to The Times.
He has never found such a consensus before, except in the GrandMet
boardroom, he says. In terms of heavyweight names his letter is reasonably
impressive although it does not quite match the list of distressed
businessmen, led by Rolls-Royce's Lord Tombs, who wrote to The Times to
complain at the Conservative Party's ditching of Margaret Thatcher in 1990.
The only names common to both lists are those of Sir John Cuckney, Sir
Patrick Meaney, Lord King and Neil Shaw. One name surprisingly absent from
both letters is that of ex-cabinet minister and Cable and Wireless chairman
Lord Young, author of The Enterprise Years.
</TEXT>
