<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Arts: ENO acquires the Coliseum
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The English National Opera has acquired the freehold of its London home, the
Coliseum, for Pounds 12.8m. The money comes mainly from the Government,
Pounds 10.8m, with the remaining Pounds 2m supplied by the Foundation for
Sport and the Arts.
For its part ENO will shortly launch a public appeal for around Pounds 17m
to raise the capital to refurbish its property. The money will be spent on
back stage and front of house improvements, and could involve a closure for
up to a year.
All the parties were in a congratulatory mood yesterday. The Minister for
the Arts, Tim Renton, was happy that his department had secured Pounds 10.8m
from the reserves on the last day of Parliament; Peter Jonas, entering his
last year as general director at the ENO, was pleased that a fast
approaching crisis in the affairs of the Coliseum - the ENO's current lease
expired in 1996 - was now permanently resolved; and the owners of the
property, Stoll Moss, was satisfied with what it described as a 'realistic'
price.
The recession in the property market, and the fact that the Coliseum is a
listed building, made the purchase price much lower than anticipated a few
years ago. The ENO will use its immediate annual saving in rent of Pounds
350,000 - it acquires the building on March 31  - to pay the legal fees of
all involved.
The co-operation of the Foundation for Sport and the Arts was vital. The
Government would have been reluctant to provide the whole sum. The
Foundation, financed by the football pools companies in an effort to ward
off a national lottery, is proving a good friend to the ENO.
The Pounds 2m grant is its largest donation to the arts and comes from the
Pounds 20m it has set aside this year for arts causes. Earlier this month it
gave the ENO Pounds 400,000 for a new computerised box office.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
