<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Brokers protest at lack of cover for Names: Allegations of
inadequate backing for stop-loss protection
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A ROW has broken out at the Lloyd's of London insurance market over the
refusal of many leading underwriters to back schemes providing stop-loss
insurance - or personal reinsurance policies  - for Names, the individuals
whose assets provide the market's capital.
Brokers argue that the lack of realistically priced stop-loss insurance
could undermine the market's capital base by leading many Names to leave.
Last year 12,500 Names bought stop-loss insurance - which covers a band of
losses beyond an amount usually equivalent to between 10 per cent and 20 per
cent of the amount of premiums underwritten by a Name.
This year many underwriters have declined to back a scheme developed by two
brokers, Harrison Stuart and Holman Wade, which is intended to provide cover
for more than 8,000 Names.
Underwriters, who are wary of high-risk business in view of the losses
recently suffered by catastrophe syndicates, are demanding rate increases of
up to 100 per cent and reducing cover by as much as 50 per cent, which makes
stop-loss cover expensive and unattractive for Names. According to Mr John
Harrison, chairman of Harrison Stuart, the insurers' attitude that stop-loss
is 'not an underwriting proposition' is sending the 'worst possible signal'
to Names.
Mr Michael Wade, chairman of Holman Wade, wrote last November that in the
absence of stop-loss insurance as many as 8,000 Names might leave Lloyd's.
It said this would place the market under 'extreme and possibly
unsustainable, pressure'. Senior brokers last week visited Mr Richard
Hazell, a leading underwriter and deputy chairman of Lloyd's, to urge him to
back the Harrison Stuart/Holman Wade scheme.
Mr Jim Payne, a broker with EW Payne who is confident that the Holman
Wade/Harrison Stuart scheme will be placed, said yesterday: 'People must get
their act together.' Mr Harrison said: 'There is no doubt that the big
brokers have the ability to concentrate the market's mind.'
It emerged yesterday that syndicate 932, one of the biggest marine
syndicates at Lloyd's with 3,102 Names, is to leave its 1989 year open.
The syndicate, which is managed by Janson Green, has Been unable to assess
its liabilities arising from exposure to US legal cases involving pollution
and asbestosis with sufficient accuracy to be able to close its accounts.
Mr Richard Youell, underwriter, said that the number of notifications of
pollution claims rose by 10 per cent last year.
The claims have emerged on policies written between 1950 and 1985. Some US
courts have ruled recently in favour of insurers in pollution cases,
supporting arguments that the cost of cleaning up a polluted site cannot be
claimed on an insurance policy.
However many of these verdicts have been appealed against, and according to
Mr Youell there is still considerable uncertainty over the size of future
claims. A decision to close the syndicate's accounts would have involved the
establishment of large reserves and would have meant heavy losses for Names.
Investigations by a Lloyd's disciplinary committee into an insurance broker
are continuing. An employee allegedly 'skimmed' insurance premiums by
charging his client more than the real cost of the premiums and retaining
the difference.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
