<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Law jobs 'too costly for many graduates'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY half of the law graduates who failed to take up their places on this
year's finals course for solicitors dropped out because they could not
afford a career in the law, according to the College of Law.
An inquiry by the college, the largest training organisation for solicitors
in Europe, found that 244 of the 508 law students who cancelled places or
failed to register at the beginning of the 1991-92 academic year had
financial reasons for withdrawing.
More than 40 per cent of respondents to a more detailed questionnaire sent
to the 244 had upper second honours degrees, and 11 per cent had already
arranged training contracts with law firms.
Nineteen per cent of the respondents had managed to obtain a council grant,
although only 6 per cent managed to get both fees and a contribution to
maintenance; 9 per cent were offered a bank loan; and 6 per cent obtained
some sponsorship from employers or potential employers. Only 2 per cent
obtained grants from charities or other foundations.
Worst affected were students from ethnic minorities and married women
returning to work after having children.
Mr Richard Holbrook, chairman of the college's management board, said the
college was 'very concerned about the extent of initial student drop-out'.
The college would continue to campaign for mandatory grants to cover fees on
the finals course and look for help from business in establishing a bursary
scheme, he said.
Mrs Yve Schelaas, a married women with four children who obtained an upper
second degree from the University of Kent, approached 20 firms in the hope
of securing sponsorship for her finals course.
'It's such a waste of taxpayers' money to educate law graduates so far and
then not enable them to finish their qualifications,' she said.
</TEXT>
