<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Advantages seen in 'single-table' deals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPANIES which bargain with several unions separately are likely to pay
higher wages and perform less well financially than companies which deal
with just one union or several negotiating together, according to a study by
economists.
The economists also find that bargaining separately with several unions
makes companies more prone to strikes lasting a day or more.
The report was compiled by Mr Stephen Machin and Mr John Van Reenen of the
economics department at University College, London, and Mr Mark Stewart of
the economics department at Warwick University. It comes when many employers
are considering whether to simplify their industrial relations by cutting
the number of unions they deal with or introducing 'single-table' bargaining
arrange-ments. Under the 'single-table' approach, several unions, often
representing different groups of workers, bargain together.
The study says data drawn from the government-funded Workplace Industrial
Relations Survey of 1984 show that what matters 'is not the presence of
multiple recognition, but whether or not multiple unions bargain en masse or
as individual entities'.
The study suggests that skilled workers benefit more than semi-skilled and
unskilled workers from fragmented bargaining. It adds that the mark-up for
skilled workers in such arrangements over similar workers covered by single
bargaining procedures is 8.3 per cent. Semi-skilled and unskilled workers
benefit by 5 per cent and 5.3 per cent respectively.
The economists say wages differ little between establishments where the
workers belong to multiple unions - but bargain jointly  - and those in
comparable units with a single union.
The evidence found by the economists about the effect of fragmented
bargaining on financial performance, measured by rising demand and the use
of plant, is less clear-cut.
They say, however, that the difference between fragmented and 'single-table'
bargaining is more noticeable among manufacturers than non-manufacturing
employers.
The study finds that bargaining arrangements have little effect on any type
of industrial action. For strikes lasting at least a day, however, a
'significant difference' is found between multiple and 'single-table'
bargaining. 'This supports the notion that workplace disputes may result
from inter-union competition in bargaining,' the economists say.
Multi-union bargaining arrangements in workplaces have long been considered
by many industrial relations experts to be a restraining force on industrial
effici-ency.
The 1968 Donovan Commission, set up by the then government, strongly
advocated moves to industrial unionism, based on single industry-wide
unions, on the grounds that inter-union competition was divisive.
Companies setting up plants almost all recognise just one union, if any.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 8
