<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Unions seek end to Civil Service pay gap
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GAP between the pay of senior civil servants and comparable white-collar
workers in the private sector is no longer justifiable, according to unions
basing their claims on a report on job security by Coopers &amp; Lybrand
Deloitte, the consultancy firm.
Senior civil servants have traditionally been paid less than their
private-sector counterparts, in part because they are less likely to lose
their jobs and face long periods of un-employment.
Their remuneration is now the subject of the most comprehensive review since
the mid 1980s. It is expected that the Top Salaries Review Body will
recommend significant increases when it reports later in the year. According
to Coopers, in a report commissioned by the FDA, NUCPS and IPMS unions,
there is ample evidence of a higher degree of turbulence and job-changing in
the private sector, and the recession is sharpening the difference.
The report says: 'However, it is important to recognise that not all
turbulence is synonymous with insecurity, and not all insecurity is
synonymous with hardship.'
Job changes, the report says, reflect a desire by private-sector managers
for wide experience and head-hunting by employers. 'Even in the midst of
recession the length of time on average between jobs does not seem to
outweigh the length of time over which financial support is available.'
</TEXT>
