<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Tokyo holds back from intervening in markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO AND AGENCIES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
TOKYO share prices showed further weakness in opening trading early today,
after Japanese authorities gave no sign of following past practice and
intervening to revive the stricken market.
Finance Ministry officials indicated instead they would rely on general
monetary and economic policies to restore confidence eventually in the
market and in the economy.
'This is now a free market,' an official said. 'We are not going to try any
of the old tricks. They will not work.'
With institutional selling continuing to put pressure on prices today, the
Nikkei index finished the morning session down 317.67 points or 1.59 per
cent at 19,599.96.
Yesterday the index failed to regain the psychologically important 20,000
level, though it finished the day up 80.47 at 19,917.63. On Monday, the
index fell through the 20,000 level to its lowest close for five years.
The last time the index fell through this level in 1990 Mr Ryutaro
Hashimoto, the finance minister, relaxed regulations to encourage investors
to buy stock. This time, his successor, Mr Tsutomo Hata, has given no
indication of making a similar move.
The ministry's change of heart is a recognition that officials' power to
manage markets has been undermined by liberalisation in the 1980s, including
introduction of stock futures trading, admission of foreign companies and
interest rate deregulation.
It also a reflects a belief that even with support from stockbroking
companies the ministry lacks financial resources to shore up equities. In
the 1960s, the last bear market, officials encouraged broking companies to
club together to maintain prices.
Bankers ruffled, Page 30; Stock markets, Page 39
</TEXT>
