<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Labour takes 5-point lead in two polls
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and IVO DAWNAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE LABOUR party last night claimed to have seized the initiative in the
opening general election battle over the economy and taxation after two
opinion polls gave it a five-point lead over the Conservatives.
Published on the eve of the launch of their election manifestos, the polls
contrasted with earlier surveys suggesting that the two main parties
remained neck-and-neck.
As Mr John Major prepared to restore the momentum of his campaign with the
launch of a manifesto setting out a distinctive Conservative agenda for the
1990s, senior ministers sought to brush aside the findings.
The ministers, who said that a shake-up in the Whitehall machine would be
among a series of new ideas in the Conservative manifesto, pointed to sharp
day-to-day fluctuations in the dozen or more surveys published since the
election was announced last week.
But after another day in which the economy and taxation dominated the
campaign, Mr Neil Kinnock claimed that the publication this week of Labour's
tax and benefit plans had given him a decisive advantage.
His optimism was reinforced by the first opinion poll taken after the
announcement of Mr John Smith's shadow Budget. The ICM poll for The Guardian
carried out yesterday put Labour on 43 per cent and the Conservatives on 38
per cent, with the Liberal Democrats on 16 per cent. The same levels of
support are shown in a Mori poll for The Times carried out before the
unveiling of Labour's tax package.
These latest snapshots of opinion will boost Labour morale in the first
crucial phase of the campaign. They came after the financial markets had
closed in London, but in New York sterling remained firm against a weaker
dollar.
In his first full day of campaigning around the country, Mr Major repeatedly
attacked Labour for its 'vindictive' plans to increase sharply the tax
burden on those earning more than Pounds 22,000.
Mr Kinnock seized on official figures showing another fall in manufacturing
output to accuse the government of 'appalling' economic mismanagement. Mr
Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, joined the row with a warning
that the recession risked turning into a 'slump', but Mr Major said the
re-election of a Tory government would quickly trigger a recovery.
The ministers said today's Conservative manifesto would translate the change
in the party's rhetoric and style since Mr Major replaced Mrs Margaret
Thatcher into a new 'agenda' for the next five years. Mr Douglas Hurd,
foreign secretary, signalled that among measures to emphasise a 'caring'
image would be a drive to regenerate the inner cities and a range of new
training initiatives. He promised rents-into-mortgages schemes for council
tenants to spread the benefits of ownership.
Alongside the plans to overhaul Whitehall - always resisted by Mrs Thatcher
 -Mr Major plans to give a commitment to a more open style of government.
The changes in the government machine involve creating a cabinet post to
oversee the implementation of the Citizen's Charter. The charter, launched
last year, will be at the centre of the government's programme to provide
better public services.
The reforms also involve a move to strengthen the Department of Trade and
Industry, which would take over most of the responsibilities of the Energy
Department. There was speculation last night that a second cabinet post
would be created to oversee a strengthened department covering the arts,
heritage and sports.
Labour's manifesto will have at its core a recovery package for industry and
jobs alongside a range of initiatives on education, health and crime.
The 10,000-word document, entitled 'Its Time To Get Britain Working Again',
combines the twin themes of the need for change and Labour's recent poster
campaign: 'Majorism Isn't Working' - itself lifted from the Tories'
successful 1979 attack on Labour.
