<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / International Company News: Mannesmann buys 47% stake in car
parts group
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By HAIG SIMONIAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MILAN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SOGEFI, the stock market quoted auto components group controlled by Mr Carlo
De Benedetti's Cir holding company, has sold its 47.97 per cent stake in
Boge, the German car parts group, to Mannesmann for L120bn (Dollars 95.79m).
Sogefi, which is 60 per cent owned by Cir, bought an initial 25 per cent
stake in Boge in 1989 and subsequently raised its holding in stages to the
present level. Boge, which has sales of about DM750m, specialises in shock
absorbers and suspension systems for vehicles, and is a European leader in
research into electronic suspensions.
The sale, which will give Sogefi an extraordinary gain of about L19bn, means
Mannesmann now owns virtually all the shares in Boge, having bought out VDO
and Commerzbank, the two main German shareholders, last August. Mannesmann
subsequently went on to buy VDO, an auto electronics group, last October.
Mannesmann's arrival on the scene put an end to any ambitions Sogefi may
have cherished of eventually gaining control of Boge, some members of whose
management had voiced misgivings about its intentions. Sogefi is already
active in shock absorber production through Rejna, an Italian company it
bought in 1986. Shortly afterwards, it consolidated its European position by
buying shock absorber makers in France and Belgium.
A Cir official denied yesterday that Sogefi had ever nursed plans to take
over Boge, on the grounds that such a move would have been blocked by the
German cartel authorities. Sogefi, which has grown rapidly in recent years
through a string of acquisitions, specialises in auto filters and suspension
systems.
Sogefi said the sale to Mannesmann could be followed by co-operation in
distributing spare parts for cars in Europe and in developing integrated
sub-systems. Sales for Sogefi group rose by almost 9 per cent to L620bn
while net profits amounted to L22.6bn in 1990, the last year for which
figures are available.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
