<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
If, like me, you find the incidence of kissing, expectoration, and feigned
injury in soccer too much to take, you are going to have to hunt around for
something to watch tonight since BBC1 devotes two hours to Liverpool In
Europe (7.00, they play Genoa) and ITV spends equal time on The European
Match (Spurs v. Feyenoord 8.00). And if, like most of us, you have also had
enough of party political bickering to last you a lifetime, matters will be
even more problematical.
Perhaps you enjoy programmes about racism; judging from their frequency the
broadcasters think we do. Trouble Behind (8.05 BBC2) visits Corbin in
America's Deep South 'to expose and confront the racism that exists even
today'. Vying with racism as the broadcasters' pet topic is New Age
airy-fairyism. QED also takes a trip to the US to report on 'a miracle
cure-all wonder drug', a herbal elixir promoted by a Swiss gentleman from a
caravan in the Arizona desert. Thank goodness the BBC has the funds for
these vital investigations.
If you want to laugh even harder, tonight's funniest programme will be a
repeat of Drop The Dead Donkey (11.00), C4's excellent comedy about a
television newsroom.
</TEXT>
