FT  18 MAR 92 / Election 1992: Leading business figures backing the Tories
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SIR ALISTAIR GRANT joined supermarkets group Argyll in 1977, and has been
chief executive since 1986. Group pre-tax profits rose from Pounds 64.6m in
the year to March 1986 to Pounds 290.8m last year. Argyll's annual report
puts Sir Alistair's remumeration at Pounds 518,000; under Labour his extra
tax burden would be about Pounds 92,000 a year, or Pounds 1,770 per week.
SIR ALLEN SHEPPARD joined GrandMet in 1975 and became chief executive in
1986. Pre-tax profits of the group have grown under his leadership from
Pounds 368m in the year to September 30 1986 to Pounds 963m last year. His
1991 emoluments are put at Pounds 713,391 (excluding pension benefits); the
rough cost to him of Labour's proposals would be Pounds 129,450 a year, or
Pounds 2,490 a week.
LORD KING OF WARTNABY has been chairman of British Airways since 1981. Since
the company was privatised in 1987, profits have risen from Pounds 162m in
that year to Pounds 285m in the first nine months of the current financial
year. BA's last report and accounts show Lord King's emoluments as Pounds
407,650 a year so Labour could cost him Pounds 71,358 a year, or Pounds
1,372 a week.
PETER DAVIS joined Reed International from J Sainsbury in 1986, becoming
chief executive later that year. The publishing group's profits have risen
from Pounds 188m in the year to March 31 1987 to Pounds 222m last year. His
emoluments (excluding pension contributions) are put at Pounds 310,569. On
that basis, Labour could cost him Pounds 52,900 a year, or Pounds 1,010 a
week.
STANLEY KALMS is chairman of Dixons, the electrical goods retailer, which he
joined in 1948. Pre-tax profits have been damaged by the recession, falling
from Pounds 102.6m in the 1986-87 financial year to Pounds 81.7m in 1990-91.
The Dixons report shows his annual remuneration at Pounds 566,132; the cost
to him of Labour would be Pounds 101,450 a year, or Pounds 1,950 a week.
Figures are based on earnings in annual report. They assume that figures
shown taken as salary (rather than other taxable benefits); they do not take
into account the proposed change in child benefit
