<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / Australians unsure over recession
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AUSTRALIA may have limped out of recession in the three months to December,
but the economy remains fragile and recovery is likely to be weak, figures
published yesterday suggest.
The picture of the economy revealed by the quarterly national accounts was
more confused than usual because of the introduction of a new statistical
definition of changes in gross domestic product.
A new measurement, GDP(A), showed growth of 0.3 per cent in the three months
to December, following growth of 0.1 per cent in the September quarter.
GDP(A) measures the average of the three traditional definitions of GDP,
based on income, expenditure and production measurements.
GDP(I), the income based measurement which is the government statisticians'
preferred index, rose by 0.4 per cent in the three months to December, but
fell 0.1 per cent in the September quarter.
The contrast between the two raises doubts over whether the economy has
fulfilled the technical definition of recovery, which requires growth over
two successive quarters.
The government statistics bureau also said the trend estimate, which
smoothes out quarterly fluctuations in the figures, remained subdued. On
this basis, GDP(A) was flat, following six successive quarterly
contractions.
Mr Paul Keating, the prime minister, said the figures showed that a ADollars
2.3bn (Pounds 980m) public spending package announced last month was 'about
right'. He said the government was 'entitled to be confident that the
economy is on the turn'.
</TEXT>
