<HEADLINE>
FT  18 MAR 92 / EC proposes airline 'open skies' next year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN airlines could be free to set their own fares from the beginning of
next year, according to proposals under consideration by European Community
governments.
Mr Karel van Miert, the EC transport commissioner, said yesterday in London
there were growing signs that a majority of EC governments favoured
accelerating the process of liberalisation of European air transport. This
included giving airlines freedom to fix air fares and introducing cabotage,
enabling an airline from one EC country to operate domestic flights in
another member state.
EC transport ministers will consider the third stage in the Community's air
transport liberalisation programme at a meeting in Brussels next week.
That meeting would not take a final decision on the third package of
liberalisation measures but a final agreement is expected in June, Mr van
Miert said. This would clear the way for 'open skies' in Europe from the
start of next year.
Mr van Miert said he had been pleasantly surprised by the progress and
degree of consensus emerging among EC governments on the latest air
transport package. 'Work has progressed well and goes beyond what we
originally felt was possible,' he said.
Agreement to allow airlines freedom to fix their fares would represent an
important breakthrough. But the Commission would retain powers to ensure
airlines did not abuse any dominant position or attempted to drive out
weaker competitors through predatory pricing and dumping.
Under the current system, scheduled air fares in Europe are governed by the
'double disapproval' system whereby an airline can be stopped introducing a
new fare between two EC countries if the governments of both countries
oppose it.
Mr van Miert suggested a system of 'consecutive cabotage' as a first step
towards full cabotage could start as early as next year. 'This would enable
an airline like British Airways to fly from London to Paris and then on to
Nice or some other place in France,' he explained. Agreement also appears to
have been reached on the criteria of licencing airlines in Europe. An
airline could be established anywhere in the Community as long as it was 51
per cent owned by EC citizens.
But Mr van Miert acknowledged the larger EC carriers were unhappy with the
Commission's proposals to set up a system of allocating 'slots' at busy
European airports to new entrants and smaller airlines.
There were also difficulties in reaching the necessary balance on a policy
for airline mergers and partnerships to ensure European airlines could
expand to compete against large foreign carriers by forging cross-border
links at the same time as not undermining competition rules.
Transport ministers from 28 European countries yesterday agreed to help east
European states upgrade their air traffic control systems and improve air
links with western Europe. This is part of the effort to harmonise and
integrate Europe's fragmented and inefficient air traffic control network.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
