<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / International Company News: Unisys sees 'small profit' in
opening term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
UNISYS, the struggling US computer manufacturer, said that it expects to be
profitable in the current first quarter in spite of continuing market
weakness and a tough competitive environment.
After several years of heavy losses, Unisys returned to profitability in the
fourth quarter of 1991. The company now expects 'a small profit in the
seasonally weak first quarter, compared with a loss of Dollars 98m, or 79
cents a share, in the first quarter last year', said Mr James Unruh, Unisys
chairman and chief executive.
'Clearly, we consider a first quarter profit another significant milestone
in our recovery. Given the environment, a profit was not a sure thing. We
remain very cautious about global economic conditions, particularly in the
first half. But we have not altered our view of 1992 as a profitable, though
difficult year,' Mr Unruh told Wall Street analysts yesterday.
Outlining Unisys' strategy, he said that the company aims to lower its costs
in order to maintain profitability in spite of weak business conditions.
With 'our continually improving cost structure, any incremental revenue we
can generate will have a positive impact on the bottom line,' he said.
Mr Unruh said that Unisys plans to continue to reduce its Dollars 3bn debt
and that the company expects to generate more than Dollars 700m in cash flow
from operations in 1992.
'We believe we were early among our computer systems competitors to reshape
our business to the new realities of our industry. There is no easy or rapid
way to solve today's challenges. But we have indeed made a new start and
will begin in 1992 to reap the benefits."
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
