<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / International Company News: Nestle wins crucial case in
battle for Perrier
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NESTLE, the Swiss food group, won a crucial round in its fight for control
of the Perrier mineral water group when a French court yesterday invalidated
the purchase of a 13.8 per cent stake in Perrier by Saint Louis, the French
sugar company.
Saint Louis is allied to Italy's Agnelli family, Nestle's opponents in its
FFr13.42bn (Dollars 2.41bn) bid for Perrier.
This is the second big court case Nestle has won in the battle. Ten days
ago, another French court froze the voting rights on part of the Perrier
shares owned by Exor, the property group that controls Perrier for which the
Agnellis are in the throes of an agreed FFr5.6bn offer.
These cases will be critical in determining Nestle's chance of winning
Perrier. The Agnelli camp, which controlled almost 49 per cent of the voting
shares, could have blocked the Swiss group's bid, but this stake is now
reduced to 31 per cent, increasing Nestle's room for manoeuvre.
Yesterday's case hinged on whether Perrier had sold the block of new shares
to Saint Louis as part of a concert party to block Nestle's bid.
However Nestle, which joined with Indosuez, the French bank, in bidding for
Perrier, will almost certainly have to raise its offer because Exor recently
mounted a counter-bid for the rest of the mineral water company's shares at
FFr1,475, the same price as Nestle.
Perrier's shares rose FFr14 to FFr1,650 in Paris yesterday on expectation of
a counter-bid. Analysts agreed Nestle would not have to bid much above the
market price to win control unless the Agnellis, who stand to make a profit
on their Perrier shares, launch another counter-bid.
Conversely the Agnellis, who have been pitted against their old ally, BSN,
the French food group which has aligned itself with Nestle by mounting a
FFr6bn counter-bid for Exor, could decide to negotiate a settlement.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
