<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Security services accused by MPs over 'supergun'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH intelligence was yesterday accused of misleading parliament over the
Iraqi 'supergun' affair by three Labour members of a House of Commons select
committee.
However, a trade and industry committee report stopped short of censuring
the security services.
The committee's two-year investigation into the saga blamed inadequate
procedures and misjudgments by civil servants, rather than ministers or the
intelligence services, for failing to prevent the manufacture and export of
supergun components by British companies.
Mr Gordon Brown, shadow trade and industry secretary, accused the government
of an 'attempted whitewash' before the general election and pledged to
launch an independent inquiry into the affair if Labour wins.
'It is now clear the British government knew of plans for a supergun long
before the official admission in April 1990,' he said. 'I want to know from
the prime minister who knew what and when, and which ministers were
involved.'
The committee's report concludes that 'knowledge within the government of
the project was like a number of people all holding pieces of a jigsaw
without realising that they were the pieces of the same jigsaw'.
Both the Ministry of Defence and Department of Trade and Industry are
censured for taking decisions on the basis of telephone conversations with
no written record, or reference to management and ministers.
The report also criticises the DTI for not requesting more documents when
Sheffield Forgemasters and Walter Somers, the British companies which made
barrel sections for the project, applied for export licences in summer 1988;
for failing to link the two orders and to keep them under continued
scrutiny; and for not checking its records and connecting the contracts with
information about the Iraqi project circulated to government departments in
late 1989.
In spite of claims during the committee's hearings that British intelligence
was kept fully briefed about the project by the supergun's designer, Dr
Gerald Bull, an amendment specifically censuring the security services was
not included in the report.
It concludes that 'the long-range gun affair raises serious and important
questions about the accountability of the intelligence services both to
ministers and to parliament'.
The attack against the intelligence services came from the Labour MPs, Mr
Doug Hoyle, Mr Jim Cousins and Mr Stan Crowther. At a sometimes heated news
conference yesterday, Mr Hoyle, MP for Warrington North, said he found it
'almost impossible to imagine' that British and other foreign intelligence
services were not aware of the project from its inception.
Mr Cousins, MP for Newcastle Central, said he was in 'absolutely no doubt
that parliament was deceived about this matter. Either the intelligence
services knew about this from the beginning or they are grossly incompetent
and ought to be sacked'.
Mr Keith Hampson, Conservative MP for Leeds North-West, wanted the report's
publication delayed after documents relating to the affair came to light
last week.
</TEXT>
