<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Election 1992: 'A fair deal for average taxpayer'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR John Smith said that Labour's draft Budget would 'provide a fair deal for
the average taxpayer' and help Britain achieve recovery from recession.
Compared with what had been announced and leaked in advance, the shadow
chancellor's proposals contained few surprises. To a considerable extent, he
has taken over last week's Conservative proposals to help business and added
some of his own, such as a one-year increase in capital allowances to 40 per
cent from 25 per cent and increased government spending on training and
providing job experience.
On personal taxation and benefits, Labour's Budget maps out a very different
philosophy from that of Mr Norman Lamont. The average taxpayer stands to be
better off under Labour, but not dramatically so. At the higher income
levels, particularly in families with only one, highly-paid earner, election
of a Labour government would result in a significant reduction in disposable
income. Mr Smith's first Budget would redistribute income from the high to
the low-paid while Mr Lamont's Budget was designed to pass modest tax cuts
to all.
If he becomes chancellor, Mr Smith will:
scrap the lower 20 per cent tax band for the first Pounds 2,000 of taxable
income announced by Mr Lamont last week;
increase the personal allowance before which income tax is paid by 10 per
cent, compared with the government indexing this by 4.5 per cent.
abolish the 2 per cent employee's contribution to National Insurance on
earnings under Pounds 54 a week.
These moves would take 740,000 people out of income tax and benefit every
employee earning up to Pounds 22,000 a year.
On benefits, Labour's child-benefit plans would provide an extra Pounds 127
a year for a family with two children. Its proposal to raise pensions by
Pounds 5 for a single person and Pounds 8 for a married couple contrasts
with last week's government announcement of extra help for pensioners on
income support of Pounds 2 a week for a single person and Pounds 3 for
couples from October.
Mr Smith said a single person on average earnings would have over Pounds 100
a year more in disposable income; an average two-earner family with two
children would gain Pounds 311.
These gains would be financed by increased levies on people earning more
than Pounds 22,000 a year. According to the Institute for Fiscal Studies
(IFS), Labour's plans would cost families earning Pounds 52,000 a year an
average of Pounds 5,500 a year. Under Mr Lamont's budget, most taxpayers
would be about Pounds 2.64 a week better off, with higher earners, at
present paying the 40 per cent top tax rate, gaining Pounds 160 a year.
Mr Smith's first Budget would fulfil Labour's long standing promise to scrap
the upper earnings limit on employee National Insurance contributions.
Employees would pay 9 per cent on every pound earned above Pounds 21,060 a
year, against nothing at present. Also, a 50 per cent higher tax rate would
apply to taxable income of Pounds 36,375 and over, so that a single person
would pay 59 per cent in tax and national insurance on every pound earned
over Pounds 40,000 a year.
The shadow chancellor also announced tougher tax treatment on certain
benefits in kind, including a plan to scrap the 2 per cent incentive paid to
people to opt out of the state earnings related pension scheme (Serps).
Labour would also keep the 0.5 per cent stamp duty on share transactions for
at least another year.
To reassure financial markets, Mr Smith pledged to take sterling into the
narrow band of the European exchange rate mechanism at its DM2.95 parity 'in
due course'.
Mr Smith also said that Labour would keep some parts of last week's
government Budget. These included the proposals to ease the burden of the
uniform business rate, the special assistance for the car industry and the
help for small businesses, including the removal of most small businesses
from inheritance tax. He also said Labour would not alter Mr Lamont's
proposals on excise duties.
Labour said its tax plans would raise extra revenue of Pounds 1.89bn in
1992-93 and Pounds 3.5bn in 1993-94, which it would use to increase
investment. This would include a Pounds 1.1bn 'recovery programme' for the
economy, incorporating the more generous treatment of capital allowances as
well as Pounds 600m spending on skills and the unemployed.
Labour's published plans contain no estimate for the cost of the proposed
capital allowance changes, though these could be expected to hit government
revenues from 1993-94. Last night Labour officials estimated the likely cost
at Pounds 600m against a recent IFS study which estimated that 40 per cent
capital allowances for one year could cost Pounds 2bn.
Labour's Budget has other gaps too, with no estimate of the impact on growth
or inflation. Labour adopted the Pounds 28bn public sector borrowing
requirement set by the government for 1992-93, but did not indicate its
future borrowing needs. It was silent on privatisation. Last week's
government Budget envisages privatisation proceeds of Pounds 8bn in 1992-93
and Pounds 5.5bn in 1993-94 and 1994-95.
</TEXT>
