   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMMUNITY health trust in Dorset announced yesterday that it expected to
agree Britain's first locally negotiated deal on pay and conditions,
signalling a move away from the national Whitley Council agreements for
health workers, Lisa Wood writes.
West Dorset Community Trust said it was negotiating a local 'reward package'
with trade unions representing its 1,200 hospital and community services
staff. This would be applicable to all staff except doctors. The package
would include performance-related pay and changes in holiday and hours
agreements.
A radical departure from the rigid pay and conditions of the National Health
Service's Whitley Council was a prime objective for the self-governing
hospital and ambulance trusts when the first wave came into operation in
April last year.
