<DATE>920317
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Looking down the barrel of the supergun: Ministry procedures
are blamed for allowing British involvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NEIL BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN British customs swooped at Teesport, Cleveland, on April 10 1990, it
seemed an unusual move. They seized innocuous steel tubes, supposedly for an
Iraqi petrochemical project.
One week later Mr Nicholas Ridley, then trade and industry secretary,
explained to parliament that 'the government recently became aware in
general terms of an Iraqi project to develop a long-range gun'.
It is now know Saddam Hussein's 'Project Babylon' aimed to produce several
giant guns theoretically capable of threatening the whole of the Persian
Gulf - and Israel  - with nuclear or chemical warheads. Moreover, three
British companies were involved, directly or indirectly, in supplying
components. How these companies were duped both by Iraq and the designer of
the supergun - Space Research Corporation (SRC) of Belgium - and how they
avoided export controls for so long, has never been fully explained - nor
has the validity of Mr Ridley's claim that the government was ignorant of
the affair until the last minute. Those looking for answers in yesterday's
report from the Commons trade and industry select committee may be
disappointed.
After a two-year investigation the committee has plumped for the 'cock-up'
theory, blaming inadequate procedures and communications in government
departments.
The events which prompted the investigation began in summer 1988, when the
Department of Trade and Industry examined two UK contracts to supply steel
tubes supposedly for an Iraqi petrochemical project. Without consulting the
Ministry of Defence the DTI decided one of the contracts - placed with
Sheffield Forgemasters  - did not require an export licence.
Walter Somers, the Halesowen steel company which had a similar contract
referred to the DTI by the Conservative MP Sir Hal Miller, a business
contact approached for advice, was told it did not require an export
licence, although the DTI referred the matter to a materials specialist in
the MoD. The specialist said he could establish no definite military purpose
for the tubes. His decision was based on two 10-minute phone conversations.
In autumn 1989 the MoD and UK intelligence services received separate
tip-offs about the Iraqi project from directors of Astra Holdings, the
British defence group. Astra had recently acquired PRB, a Belgian munitions
company, and discovered it was supplying propellants to Iraq for a very
large gun.
A report was circulated around the DTI and MoD, but no connection was made
with the contracts for steel tubes examined the year before. The MoD
specialist who examined the Somers contract did not even see a copy. This
was blamed by officials on MoD 'compartmentalisation'.
In spite of the warnings more than five months passed before British
intelligence tipped off customs officers in April 1990. Their information
prompted the seizure at Teesport of tubes made by Sheffield Forgemasters.
Further British-made components were impounded at Patras, Greece.
This version of events, however, ignores several questions raised during the
investigation. These have prompted theories of a conspiracy involving
western intelligence services and, possibly, the highest levels of
government.
The unanswered allegations centre on the following claims:
Dr Christopher Cowley, supergun project manager at SRC, has claimed that
from June 1988 Dr Gerald Bull, the gun's designer, kept British intelligence
fully informed about the project until he was murdered in Brussels in 1990.
If so, why did intelligence officers allow it to proceed and did they notify
ministers?
Evidence emerged at the weekend that the UK's Government Communications
Headquarters (GCHQ) intercepted communications regarding the supergun in
autumn 1989, which were passed to an assessment officer in the cabinet
office. From here they may have been discussed by the joint intelligence
committee and included in a weekly intelligence summary sent to some cabinet
minis-ters and the prime minister.
Mr Gerald James, former Astra chairman, has alleged his company was steered
into acquiring PRB, the Belgian company manufacturing propellants, by a
number of prominent figures with intelligence connections.
New documents were presented to the committee last week suggesting that
Sheffield Forgemasters may have had closer links with other European
companies supplying supergun components than was disclosed during hearings.
The only two legal cases brought in connection with the affair - against Dr
Cowley and Mr Peter Mitchell, managing director of Walter Somers - were
dropped on the grounds of insufficient evidence. Dr Cowley claims this was
because they would have embarrassed the government. Sir Patrick Mayhew, the
attorney general, and customs officials refused to answer the committee's
questions about these cases.
Mr Christopher Gumbley, who had been arrested by MoD police on corruption
charges, met Dr Bull in Brussels only hours before the scientist's
assassination. He says Dr Bull showed him what appeared to be surveillance
documents on members of PRB's staff and said British intelligence had used
the company for covert operations.
What could have been the motives for a conspiracy by the government and
intelligence services? Some believe the government had a covert policy of
bolstering Iraq against the threat of Islamic fundamentalism. Only when
opinions about Saddam Hussein were revised in early 1990 was the project
stopped.
It may never be established whether it was incompetence or a covert policy
that allowed arms and equipment to be supplied to a country which would end
up at war with Britain.
