FT  17 MAR 92 / Consumer body attacks Abbey over bank code
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ABBEY NATIONAL, the retail banking group, was criticised by a consumer group
yesterday after deciding not to issue its own code of banking practice for
customers.
Yesterday was the last day for banks and building societies to declare
whether they had accepted a draft code of banking practice agreed last year
by banks, building societies and consumer groups.
Unlike the other big high street banks which have all produced their own
special codes of service for their customers, Abbey National says that it
will simply place copies of the code 'Good Banking' in its branches for
those customers who ask for them.
Mr Guy Dehn, legal officer at the National Consumer Council, said he was
disappointed by Abbey National's decision. 'Good Banking is the bare minimum
that is acceptable in the market place,' he said.
Britannia, the ninth largest UK building society, has launched the first
stage of a Pounds 30m mortgage rescue scheme in partnership with Circle
Thirty Three Housing Group in East Anglia.
The scheme is part of a Pounds 1bn package pledged by mortgage lenders after
talks with the government just before Christmas about ways of reducing the
number of homes repossessed this year.
