FT  17 MAR 92 / Polytechnic changes approved
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A NEW generation of universities was announced yesterday, after the Privy
Council office gave 14 polytechnics approval to become universities under
the government's higher education reforms.
The Higher Education Act, which has just become law, allows polytechnics to
call themselves universities.
Such places as Sunderland and Huddersfield will gain universities for the
first time, while Leicester, Newcastle and Liverpool all get second
universities - each with a carefully chosen name.
Leicester Polytechnic becomes De Montfort University, Newcastle Polytechnic
will be the University of Northumbria at Newcastle and Liverpool
Polytechnic, Liverpool John Moores University.
The others are Middlesex Polytechnic (Middlesex University), Polytechnic
South West (University of Plymouth), Portsmouth Polytechnic (University of
Portsmouth), Huddersfield Polytechnic (University of Huddersfield), Kingston
Polytechnic (Kingston University), South Bank Polytechnic (South Bank
University), Staffordshire Polytechnic (Staffordshire University), Teesside
Polytechnic (University of Teesside) and Wolverhampton Polytechnic
(University of Wolverhampton).
The remaining 20 polytechnics are expected to adopt the university label
soon - almost doubling the number of English universities.
