<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Nikkei fall puts investors on tenterhooks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By STEFAN WAGSTYL and EMIKO TERAZONO
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TOKYO AND AGENCIES
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
INVESTORS in the Japanese stock market were on tenterhooks as prices
fluctuated in hesitant trading early today after yesterday's resounding fall
to their lowest level for five years.
In an effort to steady the market, Mr Tsutomu Hata, the finance minister,
said temporary and technical factors were largely to blame for yesterday's
sharp drop in share prices - which took the Nikkei index through the
psychologically important 20,000 level. He predicted the market could
recover in the not-so-distant future.
In a similar soothing vein, Mr Takeshi Noda, the Economic Planning Agency
minister, said the Tokyo price fall did not reflect Japan's economic
fundamentals.
Share prices made a modest rebound when trading began this morning, then
dipped down again before attempting a further slight recovery, with the
Nikkei index of leading stocks soon at 19,766.
Yesterday the Nikkei index lost 618.90 points or 3 per cent to close at
19,837.16. The fall below 20,000 - for the first time since February 1987 -
had been widely expected because of the market's recent weakness. It brought
the Tokyo market down 49 per cent from its 1989 peak - in contrast to New
York and London, where shares have been trading relatively close to all-time
highs.
The broader Topix index yesterday shed 19.14 points to close at 1,444.86,
its lowest since November 1986.
The Tokyo decline has meant that equities have now lost all the spectacular
gains made in the late 1980s, when a supply of cheap credit prompted a
wide-ranging financial boom. Stocks have slumped in response to higher
interest rates, declining economic growth and political turmoil in Japan and
overseas.
Yesterday's losses were triggered by a modest spate of selling by Japanese
corporate and institutional investors preparing their books for the end of
the financial year this month. Yesterday was the last day for some groups of
investors to complete transactions in time for the year-end.
Many Japanese investors early today were bracing themselves for further
falls, fearing that the poor financial health of some securities companies
and banks would undermine the market. Mr Shiomichi Kawamoto, of the
investment management affiliate of Sumitomo Life, a life company, said
yesterday: 'The Nikkei may rebound above 20,000 but the overall downward
trend is unchanged. Who will buy stocks from securities companies which are
about to collapse?'
However, a significant minority believed prices were bottoming out. Mr
Tsuneo Nakamura, managing director of Yamaichi Securities, one of the big
four brokers, said yesterday: 'Market statistics indicate that we have
already entered the final stages of the correction period.'
The Japanese authorities at first maintained a studious calm in the wake of
yesterday's sharp drop in share prices. Their stance was in contrast to
October 1990 when the Nikkei last dropped through 20,000 in intra-day
trading and the finance ministry unveiled an emergency package of
market-boosting measures.
Ministry officials now believe that changes to trading and other rules do
little to help stock prices in the long run and distort free markets. In
recent weeks they have encouraged a tightening of rules governing stock
futures trading. This was in response to complaints from brokers who blamed
the market's weakness on over-aggressive futures trading by foreign
securities companies. But latest revisions have had little effect on
sentiment.
However, politicians yesterday repeated calls for further cuts in interest
rates, urging the Bank of Japan to reduce the Official Discount Rate from
its current level of 4.5 per cent. Mr Yasushi Mieno, the central bank
governor, told a parliamentary committee he was still studying the effect of
previous reductions.
Japanese bond prices remained virtually unchanged yesterday, evidence of the
fact that investors were well prepared for the fall in equities. But on the
foreign exchanges, the yen lost ground against the US dollar.
Bankruptcies in Japan rose by 56.2 per cent in February to 1,056 cases,
reflecting the cooling of the Japanese economy, Teikoku Data Bank said,
Steven Butler adds. The pace of corporate insolvency has risen steadily on
an annual basis for the past 17 months. It said liabilities of bankrupt
companies in the fiscal year ending this month were likely to reach Y7,600bn
(Pounds 33bn).
Uneasy calm amid gathering storm, Page 21; Stock markets, Page 39
</TEXT>
