FT  17 MAR 92 / Accountancy firm settles lawsuit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ARTHUR ANDERSEN, the accountants, yesterday agreed to pay an immediate
Dollars 22m (Pounds 12.5m) in cash and to set aside a further Dollars 8m to
settle an investor lawsuit charging the firm with improper behaviour that
contributed to the collapse of Mr Charles Keating's Lincoln Savings and
Loan.
The out-of-court settlement is the latest in a series of claims against
auditors, lawyers and other consultants who worked for Mr Keating, who was
last year convicted on 17 counts of defrauding investors through the sale of
worthless junk bonds and who faces other charges.
The Arthur Andersen settlement results from a class action lawsuit by
representatives of 17,000 bond investors who sued Mr Keating, Arthur
Andersen and other firms including Ernst &amp; Young and Deloitte &amp; Touche. The
cases against those two firms are still pending.
Arthur Andersen said last night it continued to believe that the allegations
against it were unfounded. 'We have agreed to the settlement based on an
overall business strategy to avoid escalating legal costs of protracted
litigation and to get the matter behind us,' Arthur Andersen said.
Last week, in a separate development, the New York law firm of Kaye,
Scholer, Fierman, Hays &amp; Handler agreed to pay the US government Dollars 41m
to settle a federal lawsuit from the Office of Thrift Supervision (OTS), the
savings and loan industry regulator. The OTS suit charged the law firm with
withholding information about Lincoln from regulators.
