<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / EC finance ministers support legislation preventing banks
overstretching on single loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW HILL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EC finance ministers last night supported legislation aimed at preventing
banks overstretching themselves with large loans to single clients, writes
Andrew Hill. French and Spanish objections to the detail of the measure
still have to be ironed out. But all 12 ministers agreed that the ceiling on
bank loans to individual clients should be brought down to the equivalent of
25 per cent of a bank's capital.
Britain imposed a 25 per cent ceiling after Johnson Matthey Bankers, a small
bullion bank, came near to collapse in 1984, having made large loans to a
small number of dubious companies. The measure agreed yesterday should
prevent a repeat of that episode in other EC countries.
