<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Belgium to use VAT in deficit battle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BELGIUM'S new centre-left coalition government yesterday unveiled
value-added tax rates, higher excise duties and budget savings to tackle the
country's large budget deficit, Reuter reports from Brussels.
The government, sworn in just over a week ago after more than 100 days of
political stalemate, has made reducing the deficit, one of the highest in
the European Community, its top priority.
A statement issued after a special cabinet meeting said the standard
value-added tax (VAT) rate would be raised half a percentage point to 19.5
per cent and excise duties on fuel increased from April 1.
This would raise government revenue by BFr6.6bn (Pounds 110m), the statement
said. Another BFr6bn will be saved by cutting government administration
costs by 5 per cent, freezing new spending on defence and limiting civil
service recruitment. The total is still far from the BFr94bn in additional
revenue and savings the government has to find to bring the 1992 deficit
into line with the target of BFr405bn.
The government said it will also scrap the top VAT rates - 33 per cent for
luxury goods and 25 per cent for electrical goods - which will be charged at
the new 19.5 per cent.
</TEXT>
