<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Ashdown says poll reform is first aim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE 'first aim' of the Liberal Democrats would be to break free from
Britain's outdated electoral system, Mr Paddy Ashdown said yesterday as he
unveiled his party's election manifesto.
The 50-page manifesto proposes a system of proportional representation and
combines a two-year, job-creating investment programme with measures to
stimulate private enterprise.
In the event of a hung parliament, the manifesto pledges to 'neither support
nor participate' in a government which 'turns its back' on constitutional
reform.
It backs a single transferable vote system for local, national and European
elections, with multi-member constituencies for Westminster MPs.
Mr Ashdown dismissed Mr John Major's refusal to embrace proportional
representation, saying little attention should be paid to a 'political
leader with his back to the wall'.
The Liberal Democrats are proposing an increase of 1p on the basic rate of
income tax to fund an extra Pounds 2bn in education spending. The party
would also abolish the new 20p lower income tax band and increase borrowing
by Pounds 2bn to fund Pounds 4bn in extra public investment in the first
year to create 400,000 jobs.
</TEXT>
