<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Money Markets: Rates remain firm
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE money markets remained pessimistic about a cut in UK interest rates,
closing slightly firmer in a day of quiet trade.
The firmer tone followed an easier opening as the markets attempted to
correct Friday's excesses - when traders swapped rumours of a six point lead
for Labour in the April 9 election campaign. In the event, the sighs of
relief were almost audible when the polls revealed a mere one point lead for
Labour.
Traders dismissed the prospect of a cut in the short term, and the rate as
far out as one year was even nudging 11 per cent by the end of the day.
The key three month inter-bank rate closed at 10 3/4 - 5/8 per cent. On the
futures market, the June short sterling contract fell from an opening of
89.22 to 89.15 at the close.
Day-to-day funding took encouragement from the Bank of England's early
actions to stem the greater than expected shortage. Tax payments put heavy
pressure on the system, with the Bank of England initially forecasting a
shortage of Pounds 2.15bn, which was revised twice revised upwards to end at
Pounds 2.3bn.
In early operations, the Bank took out the bulk of the shortage with a
Pounds 1.6bn repo at 10 7/16 per cent and a token amount in the cheaper band
four bank bills at 10 5/32 per cent. Late morning brought a Pounds 512m
purchase of band one bank bills at 10 3/8 per cent, band three bank paper at
10 3/16 per cent, band four treasury and bank at 10 5/32 per cent.
Afternoon and late assistance totalled Pounds 200m.
As a result of the Bank's generous morning help, overnight rates were being
quoted as low as 8 per cent. However, little money changed hands at that
level, with the bulk of the cheap money being traded at noon at levels of
about 9 1/2 per cent.
In Germany, the March tax deadline drained funds from the market. This
pushed call rates slightly higher during the day from 9.50/60 per cent to
9.55/65 per cent.
Traders said they expected rates to stay at or above 9.65 per cent during
the tax period.
The Federal Reserve injected temporary reserves into the US banking system,
as funds had firmed to 4 1/8 per cent. The injection came in the form of an
unfixed three-day repurchase agreement. This means that dealers can withdraw
their collateral over the agreement's term.
The presumed Fed target for federal funds is 4 per cent.
</TEXT>
