<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / International Company News: Italians reveal 6% Fokker stake
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, RONALD VAN DE KROL and ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, AMSTERDAM, ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SCRAMBLE by European aircraft manufacturers to consolidate their
position in the cut-throat regional jet market took a new twist yesterday
with the disclosure that Finmeccanica of Italy had accumulated a 6.02 per
cent stake in Fokker, the Dutch aircraft group.
Fokker said it had been taken by surprise by the disclosure that the Italian
state-controlled company had acquired the stake, worth Fl 71.5m (Dollars
38.1m) at Fokker's current share price.
The announcement coincides with a flurry of negotiations between European
aircraft groups to try to rationalise the loss-making European regional
aircraft industry.
It comes only a week after Fokker announced it was in discussions with
Deutsche Aerospace to expand collaboration in regional jets, including the
participation of the German company in Fokker's plans to develop a smaller
version of its Fokker 100 jet.
The Fokker stake appears to reflect an effort by the Italian group to hedge
its position in the current restructuring of the industry to ensure it will
play a role in the development of a new regional jet.
Finmeccanica declined to comment yesterday. It was caught off-balance by the
disclosure of its Fokker stake.
The disclosure comes at an embarrassing moment for Finmeccanica and its
aerospace subsidiary Alenia. The French authorities have been pressing the
Italian group for an early decision on injecting Dollars 250m to increase
the capital of SGS-Thomson, the semiconductor venture in which Finmeccanica
has a 45 per cent stake.
However, Finmeccanica has been playing for time, arguing it lacks funds
while at the same time seeking some counterpart from the French for going
ahead with the capital increase. But its secret acquisition of a stake in
Fokker is unlikely to please the French.
Its Alenia subsidiary is currently a partner with Deutsche Aerospace and
Aerospatiale of France to develop a family of 90 and 120-seater regional
jets. But the German group appears increasingly reluctant to launch the new
Dollars 2.5bn programme at this stage.
Instead, it is considering forging closer links with Fokker while
encouraging the European Airbus consortium, in which it has a 37.9 per cent
stake, to develop a smaller 130 seat version of the A320 airliner. Such a
move risks isolating Alenia.
Finmeccanica's investment in Fokker came to light as a result of a new Dutch
law introduced last month requiring shareholders to disclose stakes of 5 per
cent or more in quoted Dutch companies.
Fokker would not comment on whether it believed the Italian stake was a
long-held investment or a more recent purchase. But some industry officials
suggested Finmeccanica had held an undisclosed stake in Fokker for some
time.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 27
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT921-2985</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CCQBDACCFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>920317
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / International Company News: Fugro-McClelland in partial
flotation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RONALD VAN DE KROL
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FUGRO-MCCLELLAND, the Dutch-based group of consultancy engineers, is to
float roughly one-third of its shares on the Amsterdam Stock Exchange next
month. It wants to raise up to Fl 128m (Dollars 68m) to finance a recent
acquisition in the US and to fuel growth.
The company will offer 3.2m shares to the public, at between Fl 37 and Fl 40
each, with the final price to be announced on March 30.
Trading in the shares will begin on April 7, marking the first company
flotation in Amsterdam so far this year. Of the shares on offer, 1.66m are
existing shares held by several Dutch institutional investors and venture
capital firms. The rest will be newly issued.
Fugro-McClelland, the product of a 1987 merger between Fugro of the
Netherlands and McClelland Engineers of the US, will use part of the
proceeds to repay a Fl 59m loan it took out in 1991 to finance half of its
acquisition of John E. Chance, a US surveying company.
The consultancy group, with annual turnover of Fl 310m and a workforce of
2,200, is active in geo-technical and offshore services, surveying and
environmental consulting. It has more than 100 offices in 30 countries.
</TEXT>
