<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / UK Company News: Improved engineering outcome pegs decline
at Delta to 24%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JANE FULLER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A STRONG performance from its engineering division helped to offset the
impact of weak prices on electrical cables at Delta, leaving pre-tax profit
24 per cent down from Pounds 87.1m to Pounds 65.8m in 1991. Turnover fell to
Pounds 774m, against Pounds 793.6m.
Mr Robert Easton, chief executive, said the main damage was caused by
pressure on prices in the UK power cables market as the privatised
electricity companies husbanded their cash and as European competition
intensified.
Operating profit in the cables division came out at Pounds 15.1m, less than
half the comparable Pounds 31m, on sales of Pounds 279.4m (Pounds 307.2m).
Engineering, on the other hand, advanced to Pounds 22.4m (Pounds 19.8m) on
Pounds 295.1m (Pounds 279.6m) turnover. Demand for plumbing products and gas
controls was particularly strong in Germany and Spain.
Sites were still being closed, but one positive move was the switching of
the production of fire-fighting valves from Germany to the UK, 'where costs
are much lower. It's much more efficient to manufacture in Walsall than
Frankfurt,' Mr Easton said.
Industrial services was affected by the downturn in Australia and
rationalisation costs. Profit fell to Pounds 19.5m (Pounds 24.1m).
Circuit protection suffered from destocking, reflected in profit down by
nearly Pounds 4m to Pounds 13.7m. Some cushioning was provided by the
Malaysian business and a recovery in exports to the Middle East.
Delta took the cost of redundancies and closures above the line and did not
quantify them. Mr Easton said more than 3,500 people had left the group
since 1989. The process was expected to moderate this year.
The group ended the year with net debt of Pounds 40.7m (Pounds 41.2m) for
gearing of 13 per cent. There was ample borrowing capacity to make
acquisitions, Mr Easton said. In the US, he wanted the group to grow to five
times its present sales of Pounds 48m by the mid-1990s.
Earnings per share fell to 28p (35.7p). A maintained final dividend of 9.8p
makes an unchanged total of 14p.
COMMENT
Mr Easton is perhaps the first industrialist to describe the recession as
history, especially when his company is still being affected by it. His
equanimity is to some extent justified by the resilience Delta has shown. In
spite of its 50 per cent exposure to the UK, earnings per share have fallen
by less than 24 per cent since the 1989 peak. The benefit of prompt cost
cuts and a tempering of the reorganisation bill this year should restore
profit growth, although cables markets are likely to remain difficult.
Indeed the collapse in cables profits from Pounds 10.7m to Pounds 4.4m
between the first and second halves was the most disappointing aspect of the
figures. A pre-tax forecast of Pounds 70m-Pounds 75m this year gives a
prospective p/e of about 14 on yesterday's close of 446p. Its track record,
strong balance sheet and comfortable dividend cover has earned a small
premium to the market. Although there is little scope for short-term
progress, the shares remain worth holding.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
