<HEADLINE>
FT  17 MAR 92 / Maxwell kept pension fund trustees in dark
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A 'PHANTOM' board meeting in September 1991 at which Mr Robert Maxwell
authorised stocklending from the Maxwell pension funds was unknown to
pension trustee directors, it emerged yesterday.
Confidential minutes of the board meetings of Mirror Group Pension Trustees
(MGPT), obtained by the Financial Times, show that the only directors
present at a meeting on September 2 were Mr Maxwell and his son Ian,
together with Mr Trevor Cook, the pensions manager.
At the meeting, Mr Robert Maxwell, the MGPT chairman, drafted a letter
assuring Invesco MIM, one of the managers of the pension funds, that the
programme of stocklending - lending out assets to boost income  - was
approved by the board of MGPT.
However, in one of the crucial sections of a forthcoming report by the
parliamentary committee on pension reform, to be published after the general
election, other directors of the MGPT say they were unaware that pension
fund assets had been lent out until after Mr Robert Maxwell's death in
November.
Several who were contacted yesterday said they had only recently become
aware of the September 2 board meeting and the letter to Invesco.
Stocklending is a legal and commonplace practice, but normally high quality
collateral is given until the assets are returned. Stocklending with
inadequate collateral was the mechanism Mr Robert Maxwell used to divert
Pounds 400m from the care of pension fund managers to his private companies.
One pension trustee director said yesterday the directors had received legal
advice that, though the board was quorate with two directors, decisions
could be deemed illegal if the rest of the board was not made aware of them.
Mr Cook, not a director of MGPT, confirmed that he had signed and sent the
letter to Invesco on Mr Robert Maxwell's orders. As far as he was aware the
minutes of the meeting had been filed in the normal way.
The letter, addressed to Mr James Scrymgeour-Wedderburn of Invesco MIM, says
'at your request we confirm our earlier advice that you take instructions
from Bishopsgate Investment Management', the investment company chaired by
Mr Robert Maxwell, which managed the bulk of the pension funds.
It adds: 'We concur with the stocklending operation being carried out by
Bishopsgate on our behalf'. On BIM's instructions, MIM passed it some Pounds
20m of assets for stocklending.
There is no suggestion that MIM directors acted improperly, as the letter
appeared to give them adequate authority for the transfer. The letter also
recognises that BIM, not Invesco MIM, 'is responsible to us for the holding
of adequate collateral'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
